  "notes": "Kotava — constructed international auxiliary language created by Staren Fetcey (1978, published 1993). Fully phonemic Latin orthography: one letter = one phoneme, 24 letters (⟨h⟩ and ⟨q⟩ are not used). ⟨c⟩ = /ʃ/, ⟨j⟩ = /ʒ/, ⟨x⟩ = /x/, ⟨y⟩ = /j/ (also palatalising). Five vowels /i e a o u/, no length or nasalisation contrasts; diphthongs are written ay ey iy oy uy. Stress falls on the final syllable when the word ends in a consonant and on the penultimate when it ends in a vowel; first-person verb forms are stressed finally and marked with an acute accent.",
